{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":150,"record_hash":"sha256:6ce3153e08e838c35c4f3eb932e392860ea39cb07b6303e4f1200d8dda584853","timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:04:44.268Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I mean: don’t store this as a second top-level thing:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"checked_out_refs\": [\"feature-a\"],\n  \"stacks\": [...]\n}\n```\n\nbecause it duplicates information we can put in the stack snapshot itself.\n\nBetter shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"stacks\": [\n    {\n      \"branches\": [\n        {\n          \"name\": \"feature-a\",\n          \"is_entrypoint\": true,\n          \"commits\": []\n        }\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nFor plain Git, the checked-out branch is just represented as a fake/simple one-branch stack. For GitButler, multiple stacks/branches may be visible, and `is_entrypoint: true` marks the branch/segment that `HEAD` is focused on, if there is one.\n\nWhy I prefer this: it gives consumers one model to read. They don’t need to merge “checked out refs” with “stack branches” and wonder which one wins. The snapshot says: “these are the branches visible in this workspace; this one was the entrypoint.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T01:04:44.268Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}